<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0034</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0034</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> submitted by Hannah Finney</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission of evidence will address how effectively academies have narrowed the gap for disadvantaged children.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It focuses on the favouring of successful schools in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the conversion procedure and how existing inequalities have been entrenched by the autonomy of academies with respect to admissions procedures.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unfair admissions criteria and manipulation of the freedoms granted to these schools has led to a lack of ‘narr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owing’ in the attainment gap for disadvantaged pupils.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">It recommends that the Government address this through increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> intervention in failing schools to improve the standards of state schools and give more schools in a range of areas the opportunity to c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onvert to academy status, thus affecting pupils from a wider range of backgrounds.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It also recommends that there is more transparency and accountability in the admissions systems so that schools can be held to account and are encouraged to refrain from ado</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pting selective admissions procedures.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Background:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">I am a Politics student at the University of Sheffield and I am submitting evidence to this committee as equality of opportunity in education is something I feel passionately about. I would like to show t</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">he committee that the independence of academies in being able to set their own admissions criteria is not just failing to address the attainment gap for pupils from lower incomes, but is perpetuating it. The National Audit Office found that “the gap betwee</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">n more disadvantaged students and others has grown wider in academies than in comparable maintained schools”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. Current policies are biased against those from disadvantaged backgrounds, and there are possible reforms, in making admissions procedures more tr</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ansparent and prioritising the improvement of state schools, that would help narrow the gap.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Attainment levels are fundamental to understanding educational success; the better a child performs when at school, the more highly educated and successful they a</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">re likely to become, it’s as simple as that. Just 34.6% of disadvantaged young people achieve five GCSEs at A*-C, compared to 62% of wealthier students</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. Academisation has been unable to address this gap, partly due to autonomy over admissions procedures. </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">The autonomy academies have is perpetuating an unequal system where good schools get better while poor schools get poorer, harming those from disadvantaged backgrounds more than others.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">The original academies when introduced by New Labour were built in in</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ner-city areas to address failing schools. They aimed to deliver social justice and raise standards for disadvantaged communities. This tended to benefit those from disadvantaged backgrounds as they were the most likely demographic in these areas. New Labo</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ur’s inner-city academies were “popular, improved attainment levels and were likely to deliver good value for money”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. Academies originally aimed to address the attainment gap for disadvantaged children and were doing so. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Problems with the current state o</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">f academisation:</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">The rapidity of the extension of academisation will fail to address the attainment gap for disadvantaged pupils if admissions procedures are left as they are. The Academies Act 2010 enabled schools already deemed successful by Ofsted to </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">convert to academies. The rate of academisation since then has been alarming; in May 2010 the number was 203</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt"> and by November 2013, it had risen to 3,444</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">The most recently established academies have lower proportions of disadvantaged pupils and higher </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">attainment levels. Whilst attendance and attainment at GCSE improved in academies relative to maintained schools, it must be noted that academies are less likely to have disadvantaged children in attendance and so has not narrowed the gap for them. Therefo</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">re, the post-2010 </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">academies have done little, if anything, to narrow the gap for disadvantaged children.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, due to their independence, academies can manipulate the system to entrench the existing inequalities through setting their own admissions</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt"> criteria. The Association of Teachers and Lecturers believe this is rife in academies; “the propensity for unfair admissions practices is greater in schools which are their own admissions authority, and academies suffer from a significant accountability d</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">eficit. The two factors combined make less fair admissions a certainty”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. There is widespread concern that allowing autonomy over admissions creates privilege – more desirable students at more desirable schools.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">The Academies Commission report this year w</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">as clear in its fears regarding a lack of oversight of the admissions process, with a concern that academies were structuring their admissions criteria to favour more ‘desirable’ students i.e. not those from disadvantaged backgrounds. With targets to meet,</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt"> some academies have chosen to manipulate admissions rather than addressing teaching and learning problem areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Students from a wealthier background are more likely to benefit in a diversified fragmented system of autonomous academies. They are more like</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ly to be able to exploit the system to their benefit. Wealthier families are more likely to have the financial and social capital to play the system, for example, being able to move into a different catchment area or by paying for tuition</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. Being able to p</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">lay the system is a route less likely to be taken by those from disadvantaged backgrounds and so the inequalities present in the system simply deepen.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Current Government initiatives are not doing enough to correct this gap. Pupil Premium is not enough of </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">an incentive to get academies to recruit disadvantaged pupils; the risk of not meeting targets due to the performance of disadvantaged children outweighs the possible financial benefit accrued from the premium. It was also hoped that academies would form ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">chains’ between those that are high-performing and those that aren’t, to learn from each other. However, successful academies with low numbers of disadvantaged students have not been collaborating as hoped. Collaboration is difficult in a competitive syste</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">m; schools choose to act for themselves, harming the development of a fairer, more co-operative system that would benefit those at under-performing schools</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">This submission has considered three suggestions of improvement to the current s</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ystem that it hopes would help address the current inequalities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Firstly, the introduction of quotas is an option. A system could be developed in which academies have an obligation to make sure a certain percentage of their intake is from a disadvantaged </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">background. This is difficult, however, as some academies may be situated in very affluent areas that would mean schools in that area would not meet their criteria, simply because there are not enough students from disadvantaged backgrounds rather than int</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">entional exclusion. Furthermore, without increased accountability, the enforcement of a quota system may be ineffective.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Therefore, I endorse two other suggestions I feel would have a significant impact on narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children and </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">would be possible to implement.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">The Government should shift their focus onto improving failing state schools so that they can convert to academies. These failing state schools are more likely to have disadvantaged pupils in attendance – by improving these schools through investment and a</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ttracting top teachers through schemes like TeachFirst, these schools will provide their current students with improved schooling and be able to establish themselves as academies with a big variety of pupils. Improved teaching and early interventions targe</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">ted at pupils in need are more important than the extension of the academy system</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">. This would help rule out inequality between schools and encourage the narrowing of the ‘gap’, as the original academies under New Labour did.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, academies must b</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">e more democratically accountable. They must have less autonomy in admissions procedures and adhere to a standardised set of regulations that apply to ALL schools. It must be impossible for schools to cherry-pick the type of students they want. Cases such </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">as Canary Wharf College must never happen again; only 1 of the first 60 entrants was from ‘disadvantaged’, despite half of young people in the borough being from this type of background. They must also be accountable to local government; Whitehall cannot b</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">e responsible for monitoring a huge fragmented schools system and there needs to be a middle layer to provide scrutiny and a link between schools and the Department. There have been suggestions of creating Schools Commissioners to provide this middle level</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">, though the underwhelming impact of Police Commissioners does not set a good example for this idea. Ideally, academies would have stronger links with local authorities regarding admissions. They would retain the power to set their own curriculum and have </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">external funding from sponsors, but admissions must be standardised across all schools and local authorities should retain superiority, with proper transparency regarding the process. With parents’ powers of complaint and appeal significantly eroded, this </span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">change is absolutely necessary. Academies must be publically accountable to the government and local communities too, to avoid inequality. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">This evidence has pointed out fundamental flaws in allowing academies to have autonomy over admissions procedures a</span><span style="font-family:'Microsoft Sans Serif'; font-size:12pt">nd has offered reasoned and viable suggestions on ways in which to improve the system and help narrow the gap for disadvantaged students.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Francis, B. and Wong, B., </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">What is preventing social mobility?: A review of the evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, (King’s College London, 2013), p.10</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Academies Commission, ‘Unleashing greatness: Getting the best from an academised system’, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">The Report of the Academies Commission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, (RSA and Pearson, January 2013), p.29</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Sammons, P., ‘Zero tolerance of failure and New Labour approaches to school improvement in England’, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Oxford Review of Education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, (Vol 36, No 6, 2008), p.658</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Academies Commission, ‘Unleashing greatness’, p.16</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> De</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">partment for Education, ‘Open academies and academy projects in development’, 8 November 2013, (http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/leadership/typesofschools/academies/b00208569/open-academies, accessed 09/12/2013) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Academies Commission, ‘Unleashing grea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">tness’, p.65</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Francis and Wong, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">What is preventing social mobility?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, p.16</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Clifton, J., ‘Introduction’, in Clifton, J. (ed.), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Excellence and Equity: Tackling educational disadvantage in England’s secondary schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, (IPPR, June 2013), p.14</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Clifton, J. and Cook, W., ‘The achievement gap in context’, in Clifton, J. (ed.), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Excellence and Equity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, p.26</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>